\title{Towards Physically Grounded Digital Twins and Beyond}
\import{base-macros}
\author{kellenkanarios}
\tag{public}
\tag{action-perception}

\section{Building Digital Twin}{
\p{3D-reconstruction is not \strong{actionable} i.e. we can reconstruct a room with a cup but if you try to lift the cup the whole image moves (cup is attached to counter).}

\p{[Drawer](https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.15278)}
\ol{
\li{Anchor gaussians around the zero level-set}
\li{Scene decomposition. Identify interactable and actionable objects}
\li{Use LLM for reasoning over objects i.e. density, types of joints}
\li{Recover invisible regions via differentiable rendering + generative modeling}
}
}

\section{Learning From Humans}{
\p{Real-to-sim-to-real: record environment -> build simulation of environment -> train in simulator -> deploy in real world.}
\p{Ideas:}
\ol{
  \li{Object state as an anchor}
  \ul{
    \li{Get rid of human.}
    \li{Find corresponding actions that match object states in trajectory.}
  }
  \li{Still not robust for precise movements.}
  \li{Test-time alignment}
  \ul{
    \li{Unroll in real world}
    \li{Replay in simulation}
    \li{Align}
  }
}
\p{RL -> Imitation Learning}
\ol{
  \li{Do imitation learning on noisy trajectories.}
  \li{Use noisy robot \strong{and} human trajectories}
  \li{Use classifier to try to predict whether trajectory is human or robot}
  \ul{
    \li{Noise here is the end noise in the diffusion training phase.}
    \li{Only use indistinguishable trajectories.}
  }
}
\p{Upshot is that they can "augment" robot data with human data in the diffusion training phase by including human trajectories when sampling high noise.}
}
